          "body": "Verse 10 is the most important verse in the psalm: 'Then I said, It is my grief, that the right hand of the Most High has changed.' The precise meaning of this verse is much debated — the Hebrew is compressed and the NASB's rendering ('it is my grief that the right hand of the Most High has changed') places the grief on the side of divine change, while other translations read 'this is my anguish: that the right hand of the Most High changes' as itself the turn — I will appeal to the changeless right hand. Either way, verse 10 is the moment of resolve. The three verbs that follow in verses 11-12 — 'I shall remember,' 'I will meditate,' 'I will muse' — are all first-person volitional futures. This is not a mood shift; it is a decision. Asaph does not feel better; he chooses a different content for his meditation. The diagnosis embedded here is precise: the problem in verses 3-9 was not that Asaph was meditating but that he was meditating on God's felt-absence rather than God's demonstrated acts. The prescription is not less meditation but redirected meditation — from the silence of the present to the thunder of the past."
